Last month I met this guitarist @blind_man_drew from the band @lakedubmusic and I loved his vibe!  It reminded me how much I love guitars and how much I wish that I could learn to play the guitars, both acoustic and electric.  In fact, I do own one of each, but they have been put away, and I haven't practiced enough to be any good!  Today I am taking out my acoustic and committing to practicing at least a few minutes a day!  I am finally  mounting that guitar on the wall to make it easier to just grab and at least try to work on that muscle memory for my hands. Wish me luck!

Yes I know I'm a dork, but yesterday I was trying to teach this little girl how to fly these little bamboo dragonfly toys when I caught myself not only surprised it worked, but suddenly fascinated by how ingenious yet simple and and clever it was. Clearly, you can see me in awe and having way too much fun with it! 🤭

 Anyhow, what I am recalling today is that when I was 18, I had fractured my skull in a motorcycle accident. A head on collision with a drunk driver catapulted me through the air (without a helmet) and I landed directly on the crown of my skull.  What followed was a 40% loss of hearing in my left ear and a doctor telling me I would likely never play a contact sport ever again.  That alone was devastating because I had been quite the athlete for most of my life and for the next 10 years I would get migraines, and headaches triggered by any exertions or motions involving standing up too fast, bending over or just accelerating my heart rate. I tried to fight through it, ignoring my doctor, and I continued to exercise and train despite my limitations of having to wait out the pulsing, pounding, throbbing pain in my head between any exercises. Thankfully, throughout those 10 years I could sense they were becoming less and less frequent or intense and I remember, at the beginning, thinking how even the simple sound of the wind blowing in my ears as I ran or rode my bicycle was the most amazing sound! It was like the most beautiful music I'd ever heard or that feeling you get when you hear a song you used to love but hadn't heard for so long that you'd forgotten how beautiful it was! Yesterday I felt that. Looking up to watch that bamboo dragonfly soar didnt make me dizzy. Running and bending over to pick it up didn't cause a sudden onslaught of a pounding throbbing pain in my head.

 I am so grateful not just for the absence of the pain but for that one person or persons who invented this simple little toy during the Jin dynasty China around 320 A.D. (Yes I Googled it.) Here I am almost 2,000 years later marveling and getting so much joy and appreciation for life because of something you created.  Thank you. 🙏
